Author-Name: Richard Hornbeck  
Title: The Enduring Impact of the American Dust Bowl: Short- and Long-Run Adjustments to Environmental Catastrophe 
Abstract:
 The 1930s American Dust Bowl was an environmental catastrophe that greatly
 eroded sections of the Plains. The Dust Bowl is estimated to have
 immediately, substantially, and persistently reduced agricultural land
 values and revenues in more-eroded counties relative to  less-eroded
 counties. During the Depression and through at least the 1950s, there was
 limited relative adjustment of farmland away from activities that became
 relatively less productive in more-eroded areas. Agricultural adjustments
 recovered less than 25 percent of the initial difference in agricultural
 costs for more-eroded counties. The economy adjusted predominantly through
 large relative population declines in more-eroded counties, both during
 the 1930s and through the 1950s. (JEL N32, N52, Q15, Q18, Q54)
