Template-Type: ReDIF-Article 1.0
Author-Name: Pascal Michaillat  
Title: Do Matching Frictions Explain Unemployment? Not in Bad Times 
Abstract:
 This paper proposes a search-and-matching model of unemployment in which
 jobs are rationed: the labor market does not clear in the absence of
 matching frictions. This job shortage arises in an economic equilibrium
 from the combination of some wage rigidity  and diminishing marginal
 returns to labor. In recessions, job rationing is acute, driving the rise
 in unemployment, whereas matching frictions contribute little to
 unemployment. Intuitively in recessions, jobs are lacking, the labor
 market is slack, and recruiting is easy  and inexpensive, so matching
 frictions do not matter much. In a calibrated model, cyclical fluctuations
 in the composition of unemployment are large.
